(Practice: HTTP Performance & Persistence, DNS Resolution Mechanics, Network Performance Metrics) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Question 1) Tj
T*
(In the DNS iterative resolution process, when a local DNS server queries a Root DNS) Tj
T*
(server for the IP address of 'www.example.com', what is the typical response from the) Tj
T*
(Root DNS server?) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(A. The final IP address of 'www.example.com') Tj
T*
(B. The IP address of the TLD server responsible for the '.com' domain) Tj
T*
(C. The IP address of the Authoritative server for 'example.com') Tj
T*
(D. A notification that it has forwarded the request to the TLD server recursively) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Answer: B) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Solution:) Tj
T*
(In an iterative DNS query, the Root server does not resolve the name itself. Instead, it) Tj
T*
(refers the local DNS server to the TLD server responsible for the suffix \(e.g., .com\),) Tj
T*
(which is the next step in the hierarchy.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Question 2) Tj
T*
(How does the use of HTTP/1.1 persistent connections without pipelining affect the) Tj
T*
(retrieval of multiple objects from the same server compared to non-persistent HTTP?) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(A. It allows the client to use UDP for faster image transport while keeping HTML on TCP.) Tj
T*
(B. It enables the client to send all requests simultaneously without waiting for any) Tj
T*
(responses.) Tj
T*
(C. It keeps the TCP connection open, saving the RTT associated with the TCP handshake) Tj
T*
(for subsequent objects.) Tj
T*
(D. It reduces the size of the HTTP request headers by using binary compression.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Answer: C) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Solution:) Tj
T*
(Persistent connections allow the TCP connection to remain open after an object is sent,) Tj
T*
(which eliminates the 1 RTT overhead of the TCP handshake for all subsequent objects) Tj
T*
(requested from the same server.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Question 3) Tj
T*
(During the DNS resolution process, which of the following best describes the primary) Tj
T*
(responsibility of an Authoritative DNS Server?) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(A. It acts as the primary cache for the local ISP's users.) Tj
T*
(B. It resolves top-level domains like .com and .net into IP addresses.) Tj
T*
(C. It performs the recursive search on behalf of the client's resolver.) Tj
T*
(D. It provides the definitive mapping of a hostname to an IP address for a specific) Tj
T*
(organization's domain.) Tj
T*
